					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="http://fredrikdeboer.com/2014/02/01/online-education-and-the-desperate-need-for-educational-realism/#comment-4161">
							<time datetime="2014-02-01T16:05:08+00:00">
								1 February 2014 at 4:05 pm							</time>
						</a>
											</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>In a sense, I think you&#8217;re perfectly right: he&#8217;s making a  typical academic argument in describing a change that he abdicates any responsibility for&#8211; one which, we should be clear, will leave many worse off, but not him (the boys in Davos love his work)&#8211; and I am making a political argument, that the change which he merely describes is a ruinous direction not just for higher education but for our country, and one which will leave both far worse off in the long run. He is describing a change in which he has no great personal stake. I am opposing that change out of both personal and societal need. Which one of these you value more is a matter for you and your conscience.</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

				<div class="reply">
					<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/02/01/online-education-and-the-desperate-need-for-educational-realism/?replytocom=4161#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-4161", "4161", "respond", "1046")'>Reply</a>				</div><!-- .reply -->
